          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              Perkovic’s immense popularity in Croatia reflects prevailing
              nationalist sentiments in the country 30 years after the war
              ended. Credits: PCNEN</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The what:</strong> Pro-Nazi singer Marko Perković, known as
            Thompson, sparked controversy during a concert in Zagreb, Croatia.
            He performed a song that starts with the salute “Za Dom, Spremni”
            (“For the Homeland, Ready”), which was used by <i>Ustasha</i>,
            Croatia’s WWII fascist regime (<a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-9-jul-25-spotlight-h1-2-see-video?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >see video</a
            >). The salute is banned in Croatia but still surfaces in far-right
            gatherings.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            <strong>The reaction:</strong> Critics called the concert a global
            disgrace and Europe’s largest fascist rally since WWII, accusing
            Croatian leadership of tolerating hate speech and whitewashing
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-9-jul-25-spotlight-h1-3-its-fascist-past?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >its fascist past</a
            >. However, the EU remained silent over this issue.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            <strong>The history:</strong> At the height of their regime, the
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-9-jul-25-spotlight-h1-4-ustasha-massacred?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Ustasha massacred</a
            >
            over 300,000 Serbs, 30,000 Jews, and 29,000 Romani people throughout
            their four-year reign of terror. Led by Ante Pavelić, the regime was
            known for its genocidal fascist government. Similar to Nazis, the
            Ustasha operated
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #06266d;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-9-jul-25-spotlight-h1-5-jasenovac?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >Jasenovac</a
            >, which is one of the notorious concentration camps infamous for
            their extreme methods of killing.
          </p>
